{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"964dd08d-9be7-499a-981c-549499c22a6c","content":"The directory appears to be empty — there's no workflow file here for me to modify. But here's a concise guide on switching to **NuGet trusted publishing (OIDC)**:\n\n### What to change in your GitHub Actions workflow\n\n**1. Add `permissions` for OIDC token:**\n```yaml\npermissions:\n  id-token: write   # Required for OIDC\n  contents: read\n```\n\n**2. Replace the `dotnet nuget push` step:**\n\nBefore (API key):\n```yaml\n- run: dotnet nuget push **/*.nupkg -s https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json -k ${{ secrets.NUGET_API_KEY }}\n```\n\nAfter (trusted publishing):\n```yaml\n- uses: actions/setup-dotnet@v4\n  with:\n    dotnet-version: '8.x'   # or your version\n\n- run: dotnet nuget push **/*.nupkg --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\nNo `--api-key` flag — the OIDC token is used automatically once the NuGet side is configured.\n\n### What to configure on nuget.org\n\n1. Go to **nuget.org → Manage Packages → your package → Trusted Publishers**.\n2. Add a new **GitHub Actions** publisher, specifying:\n   - **Repository owner** (your org/user)\n   - **Repository name**\n   - **Workflow filename** (e.g., `publish.yml`)\n   - Optionally restrict to a **branch/tag** or **environment**.\n3. Remove the `NUGET_API_KEY` secret from your repo once verified.\n\n### Summary of changes\n\n| Area | Old | New |\n|---|---|---|\n| Auth | `secrets.NUGET_API_KEY` | OIDC (`id-token: write`) |\n| Push command | `dotnet nuget push ... -k $KEY` | `dotnet nuget push ...` (no key) |\n| nuget.org config | API key | Trusted publisher entry |\n\nIf you share your workflow file, I can make the exact edits for you.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fee6102f-4b1a-44e1-bb9c-31d154c45094","outputTokens":508},"id":"efbb0f1c-ff00-4c40-905a-4bdc21f19598","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:37:07.642Z","parentId":"22c2e31c-c8a8-49d6-86a2-10e4d209921c"}
